segments.text: For example, at Penn, the subvention was $200,000 a year and free use of investment money and free space.
At A&M, the subvention is $330,000 a year, free space, free use of investment money, and these funds that we have
That amount to, you know, if you take the total amount that's in these funds, it's around $4 million.
And those funds are very important to the financial stability of this press.
They can't suffice alone.
We also need the subvention.
But between the funds and the subvention,
This press was far better off than any other press I had seen.
I had served on a review committee at Northwestern, which was in very bad shape financially, and had serious problems.
At Cornell, where they were losing money and didn't have financial support.
The university was supporting them, but grudging them.

So I felt one of the reasons I came here was because it did have both the psychological and emotional support from its administration that Henry Quest needed, and it had financial support better than any other place.
So those were the factors, probably, Henry, that convinced me.
Okay, now, when you arrived, how were you?
Are you disappointed?
Were your perceptions okay?
No.
I think I got what I bargained for.
I thought that this place was every bit what I suspected it was.
There was only one surprise, and it escaped me because I didn't have a base for it, and that is the bureaucracy of a state university.
has been my biggest frustration at A&M.
It's not anything that causes me to go home at night and go to sleep.
But it is more frustrating to deal with than what I had to deal with.
And this is less of an entrepreneurial kind of institution than Penn was.
Penn was very entrepreneurial.
And so at Penn, the money went to people who demonstrated that they could make money for the university
do what they had to do for the university.
Here, it's more bureaucratic.
It's political here.
And you could, in my judgment, you could be one of the best managers or administrators around.
And if you're not doing it politically or from a bureaucratic point of view, you won't get any more money.
They give money to the people who demonstrate.
In fact, I wonder if sometime this
if the efficiency of this press might not have targeted the press in terms of the financial.
It did.
Robert Smith, for example, targeted it because it was being successful financially, so they went after it.
At Penn, they would give it more money because they said, you're doing terrifically.
And that's one thing I had to...
I had to come to grips with when I came here.
I mean, some of the staff, I would say things at our advisory council meeting where I would report financially what we were doing and how well we were doing.
And Diana Hine would come up to me and say, don't tell them that, because they'll take our money away if you do that.
And I said, well, I was taken aback by that.
I said, well, no.
I said, if you're doing well, you should tell people that, and you should be rewarded for it.
That's right.
Bureaucrats don't think that way.
That's the difference between the way an entrepreneur thinks and the way a bureaucrat thinks.
And so that has had to be something I've been doing.
Good, because I have that in the text already.
And I haven't focused it, but it's there.
Do it, because that's a clear factor in this university.
That was the only explanation for part of what was going on.
It's classic that a Robert Smith,
would do that.
He's a classic bureaucrat.

And so he goes after people who have money, so he takes it away from them and would give that money to someone that was politically sensitive for him, that would accomplish his goals, his objectives, that sort of thing.
And to me, that was the wrong thing to do.
Now, that didn't happen to me.
It hasn't happened to me.
But the people here were fearful that it would happen.
Yes.
Yes, I know.
I picked that up several levels.
Yeah.

I continue, even though I know that there are bureaucrats here, and there are people who think that way, I still have confidence that if you demonstrate to people that you're accomplishing the goals that you set out to be, like my goals are two goals.
I've got to enhance the reputation of the press and the university by virtue of our publishing program.
And I have to do that in a financially responsible way.
And I feel that
If I do that, I should tell people about it and not worry that they're going to take money away from me.
I would prefer not to do that.
So at the advisory council meeting, Ray Bowen goes to that meeting, Barry Thompson goes to that meeting, and I give a report.
And I tell them what we're doing financially.
We're doing extremely well financially, and I never...
for the moment hesitated, or blushed, or anything like that.
I told the facts.
And I had confidence, maybe wrong, that they would say, this guy's doing what he's supposed to do.
That's right.
And the other side of that coin is, the money placed with a press is well-placed.
Yes.
It pays dividends.
If I were president, that's the way I would think.
That's the way it should be.
That's the way I would run the university.
I would put money in the hands of people who can demonstrate that they know what to do with it.
And the ones who don't, I would not give them any money, or I'd get rid of them.
That's right.
It doesn't always work that way.
No, it doesn't.
So when you arrive, what are your first administrative acts or encounters?
Well, the first thing we had to do at that point, there are many things, but one of the crucial things was to decide on what kind of a publisher we wanted to be.
Did we want to become a regional publisher in Frank's version of that?
Did we want to become something more than that?

And I had decided after my interviews here, and based on what my own goals are as an individual, as a publisher, that we should maintain, indeed maybe even strengthen, our ability as a regional publisher, but at the same time start becoming more of a scholarly publisher,
with the ability to reach an international audience and become much more important as an international publisher and a national publisher.
So I wanted to make sure that the staff felt that way too and the staff did.

You know, we talked about what we should do and how we should do it, what was important to us, and the staff wanted to go beyond being a regional publisher because they were getting the criticism too.
Gayla and Mary Lynn, who sat in the search committee meetings.
Gayla was a member of the search committee.
They would hear Ham Hill say, you know, I think we have a backward press.
It is nothing but a regional publisher.
We are not known by my colleagues around the world or nationally.
And it's an embarrassment.
And he would say those things.
And so they knew that their survival
was dependent upon the goodwill of the faculty and our reputation.
They were worried about it.
They knew that if Ham Hill went to Ray Bowen or to the provost and said things like that, that it might affect their future.
So they were 100% behind the idea.
So what we decided to do was to... Now, did you have sort of a series of
Or is this just part of the usual schedule of events in terms of ?
Well, first of all, I made it a practice for us to have biweekly staff meetings.
And they used to have weekly meetings.
They were meeting too much with the staff.
The whole press would meet with the staff.
So I changed that to making it just the departmental managers meeting bi-weekly.
And then I met weekly with each departmental manager.
And then I encouraged each staff member to do the same thing with each manager, to meet with their staff.
But we did this both formally as well as informally.
and we decided what areas we would focus on.
You know, we would get out of areas where we were not a player, not a significant player, and we would focus on areas where we were a significant player.
Okay, can you define those?
Sure, sure.
They're areas that won't surprise you.
From a regional point of view, we wanted to maintain our, and indeed strengthen our position in Texas history, southwestern history, military history,
But we clearly said we wanted to do everything, if not more, than what we had been doing in the regional areas.
We also wanted to expand areas where we had some presence.

needed to become more of an international publisher such as natural science or natural history nautical archaeology where we were we had an international reputation in a field that is a very small field but was good for us because this university has a reputation there we've been doing books there so nautical archaeology was another we wanted to start
publishing in Presidential Studies because of the Bush Library, because we knew that would provide opportunities.
So we wanted to do an international effort there.
And we hired consulting editors.
We started a series fund.
Joe Hughes gave us $50,000.
So Presidential Studies was an area where we wanted to speak anthropology.
How did you get that $50,000?
I actually got it by talking with Joe Hughes.
Joe Hughes was a guy who is an Aggie who's made money in the oil business.
And he and I started talking, and we wanted to know what opportunities there were for the press.
I talked to him about presidential studies, about giving one to know how much money.
I told him a minimum of $50,000, but we would prefer $100,000.
He ended up giving us $50,000.
We tried to get $100,000, but we couldn't get it.
You know, just as simply as that, just talking to a certain person was interesting.
Where did you run into him?
Frank Hubert, who used to be the chancellor of this place, told me about him.
And he is Frank's nephew, or something like that.
It's related to Frank.
And so we first started talking on the phone.
And he was impressed with the fact that Frank used to get a free copy of every one of our books.
And he worked me over for our giving him them.
We send him a copy of every one of our books when we publish, as we do all the other administrators around here.
But he would not have given us the money
did not do that.
It was important for him to see what was happening.
Yeah, and he likes books.
He's a book lover, you know, so that way we were able to tie his interest in books.
That's what I asked John.
I said, do you like books?
Yeah.
I suspected if you asked Joe Moore the same question, he might say the same thing.
I don't know.
I don't know if I asked Joe that.
I think I did.
And I think that's basically, if I didn't, that's the response.
I think people who give money to presses have to like books, but these two guys are exceptional.
They've given us money.
I think they like Frank Wardlaw, and they, you know, someone convinced them.
Yeah, they're people perfect.
Yeah.
They saw Frank as a visionary, and probably, you know, bought into him.
Anyway, Joe Hughes...
gave us money because, I think, of his love for books.
And he wanted to do something for his university, so we got him to do it that way.
But presidential studies, anthropology, borderland studies, nautical archaeology, architecture, these are all fields where we had some potential or presence, and we said,
These are the areas we want to focus on and build a reputation internationally.
We also wanted to build on some strengths at A&M, like agriculture and vet medicine.
And so we're trying to build a series in those areas too, but they are not as
a higher priority for us at this point because we have so many fish to fry in this other area.
And we don't have a lot of people to do acquisitions, so we have to focus on areas where we have the highest potential.
And those areas are basically what I just told you.
Most of the stuff that Mary Lynn does, for example, is borderlands, presidential studies,
Western history, Texana.
Most of the stuff that Noel does is military history, natural science, architecture, nautical archaeology.
So those are areas where we're trying to build our architecture.
Have you seen anything on the list that we really don't need to make an area that
How about the arts here?
Where do you want to go?
Well, Texas art, because we have money, and Joe Moore, Joe Bay, we continue to do those, and we will.
We see that as part of the regional thing that we should maintain.
That's not an area where we said, let's get out of it.
How many times have I said this?
decided to get out was philosophy.
And that proved to be very ticklish politically, because Herman Sadekamp had, I think, been signed as an editor.
And we had to tell him that we didn't know what to focus on.
Performing arts, that was a field we were in.
We dabbled in literature and literary criticism, and we felt that that was an area where we either had to go in in a big way or get out, and we decided to get out of it.
International history, like British history or European history, we felt was not important to us.
I think Balkan studies were there.
Eastern European studies we see as more of a, not just history, but that one is where we decided to focus.
where we felt we had a shot.
But we didn't want to do 20th century European history books, or ancient history books, or medieval history books, or things like that.
And we had done an occasional book there.
Journalism, we said no.
We had done some books there.
We didn't want to do any books there.
We said literature, folklore.
Folklore only insofar as it relates to Texas history and Texana, then we would do folklore.
Medical humanities, you know, getting out of that field.
Performing arts, you know, film, music, theater, getting out of that.
That's OK. Education.
Sociology.
Sports.
We had done the occasional sports, but we said no.
So those are basically the areas we got out of.
The areas we stayed in are the ones that I've already mentioned.
Our strong suits are Texas history, natural science,
Nautical archaeology, borderland studies.
What about economics?
We don't regard it as a strong field, but because we have a series fund, we want to continue to publish them.
We are publishing them.
Wherever we had series money, we felt that we had a presence.
We decided to stay in.
But if we didn't have money, we didn't have a presence, we decided to get out.
So this is one of the major things that I had to do when I came here, was to decide what kind of publisher we wanted to be and what fields we wanted to focus on.
And we did that as a staff, and we used certain criteria to make the judgment.
Financial support, presence,
whether the field was competitive or not competitive, and whether we could never make a dent no matter how much money we had because the field was just dominated by too many other people.

But in scholarly publishing, you don't have to worry about that one too much because none of the fields are, while there are dominant publishers, you can become a scholarly publisher without difficulty if you have the money.
What are your aspirations in terms of production for the press, in terms of volume, numbers of books?
When you came, we were running 35, 40.
Between 35, it varied between 30 to 35 books.
Maybe 40.
We're now doing about 60.
That is, in this fiscal year, we will do 61 books.
We took our two catalogs and counted the books.
We're about 61 books now.
When we built our long-range plan, we talked about doing 100 books a year.
And we ultimately decided against it because we felt, the staff felt strongly about this.
We felt that if we became that big a publisher, we would have to start changing the culture.
We would have to expand it.
We would have to get more money.
We would start interfering with our daily lives more than we wanted to.
So they're very proud of the family.
They are.
And Frank built it on a family basis.
I'm not a family publisher.
Unlike Frank, I believe that if you start mixing family with business, you have problems.
The big problem, in my mind, when you're running a family business, so to speak, is if you have to fire someone, you can't do it.
Try firing one of your children, for example.
You can't do it.
So I have strong management feelings about whether you should become as family-oriented as Frank was.
Frank got away with it.
Frank did it.
Frank exploited it.
But it's not my style.
It doesn't fit the modern world very well.
No, it doesn't.
It's a different era.
But that is part of the culture.
That's what he... That was part of the Stetter problem.
The family got disrupted.
Yeah, that's right.
And I don't know if Stetter knew enough about management to... Well, he didn't.
He didn't know enough about management to even recognize that probably it was a family management notion around here.
Although maybe he did.
Maybe unfairly.
But he got him in trouble.
Certainly did, yeah.
So you backed off, and you're kind of settled back to a, what, 60, 75 titles, or do you have a real target?
I don't think we, you know, we do.
I'd say that we're trying to maintain around 60, 65 titles.
Why?
We think that's optimum for the number of people we have here and for the kind of environment we want to maintain.
We go beyond that.
We're going to have to expand the place physically, expand it in terms of personnel, and we think that given the conditions that exist in the industry today, it's probably not a wise thing to do.
Tremendous problems in the industry.
Okay, what kind of problems?
That's what I want to talk to you about, too, in a little bit.
Where do you see book publishing going, especially university book publishing?
What's out there now?
The big problem that's out there now is that the scholarly monograph is under serious directs.
That is, libraries, the principal purchasers of scholarly monographs, are cutting back and spending more money on technology than they are on books.
And so every university in France that publishes scholarly monographs has seen their
their sales declined dramatically.
That's one of the wisdoms that Frank had.
Frank knew 20 years ago that scholarly publishing was deficit publishing.
He knew that if he just did scholarly monographs, he'd go out of business, or that the administration would stop supporting him.
So he said, I'm going to do books that are regional significance.
Those books sell.
And I like doing them anyway, and I'll keep the rules, the financial rules away from the door, and I'll accomplish what I believe in, and that's the way to do it.
The problem is, you know, that works financially, but it doesn't keep the academic books up.
You know, so guys like Ham Hill and Silver and other people that Frank had trouble with got after him because he was too conventional.

So the trick today is, if you're running a university press, is you've got to be financially responsible, and you've got to accomplish what universities expect university presses to do, which is to contribute to scholarship, enhance the reputation of the university, keep the faculty happy.
So doing that today is tougher than it has ever been.
The libraries aren't buying books.
Even the people who are publishing saleable books, like regional books and trade books, those books are being returned.
The superstores now are buying these books in great quantities, but they're returning them in even greater quantities.
Oh, I know.
They are.
I know.
I've personally experienced that.
Yeah.
So the trick is you need to publish, in my view, a variety of books.
You can't just do regional books.
You can't just do scholarly monographs.
You've got to do textbooks, professional books, reference books, and electronic things as well.
And you've got to do that within a financial framework that is consistent with what the person expects.
Yeah.
Can you, for example, do a text type book?
Absolutely.
Absolutely.
There's always been some constraint, at least talking, for example, to Boyd, I guess.
You always worry about the charitable philanthropic status of the press.
If you start joining the marketplace, what happens?
I think that's enough.
Unnecessary.
The University Press is long before Lloyd Lyman was in the University Press.
Well, Chicago, of course, is the classic.
Chicago, I mean, absolutely.
I mean, when I was a student, I used a Chicago book that was called Animals Without Backbones.
Now, this was back in 1950.
That was the best-selling... General Biology.
Yeah, it was the best-selling invertebrate zoology book.
I mean, Lloyd had a
different notion of that.
Lloyd was from the old, he was from the August Fruget School of Books, which was, you know, pristine scholarly monographs where, you know, you don't dirty yourself with commercial kind of things.
And now, I may be miscasting him, but university presses have been publishing textbooks as
ever since probably they've been in business.
Some of them even started doing textbooks.
And you can do textbooks.
You can't do the basic blockbuster introductory biology books.
That's a commercial gain.
But you can do the supplemental pieces.
You can do the supplemental books.
And how many university press books have you used on a supplemental basis in teaching history courses?
I think you used a number of them over the years.
Certainly.
I tried to, of course.
Exactly.
Vandiver's, whatever, Blood Brothers.
Sure.
20% of our business is probably...
I think there's a place for that.
Absolutely.
I think that's a big opportunity there.
Absolutely.
There's a place for us in reference publishing, and we do reference publishing.
There's a place for us in professional publishing, and we do professional publishing.
You know, I think the answer is you've got to do a variety of different types of books.
But you need to focus on a smaller number of areas where you have strength, presence, and the financial ability to do what is important.
And so that's what we're setting out to do.
And I think Frank set out to do that in regional publishing.
And he would do the occasional scholarly monograph to keep
some people happy, and probably to justify the fact that he was a university press.
But there are now university press directors that are saying, we can't survive doing these kind of labels.
We've got to become a trade publisher.
And I think if they do that, they're headed into a disaster.
First of all,
Why does a university need a trade publisher?
I mean, if I was Ray Bowen, it's the last thing in the world I'd want is a trade publisher.

But I'd certainly want a scholarly publisher to enhance our reputation, and to help spread the word about A&M, and to give us visibility, and to be able to say to ourselves, we're a research university, and we disseminate and diffuse that research
through books and other electronic products.
So that's, in my view, the way university presses have got to operate in the future.
And I think they will.
And I think that they have been doing that in the past.
It's just that some of them have done things a little bit differently.
Some of them have done like a pen.
95% of the books we did were scholarly modern books.
That was strictly a scholarly publishing and we had the support of the university to do that and that's the way we did our business.
Frank said
We're not going to do scholarly monographs.
First of all, probably I don't like them too much.
Secondly, they don't make money.
Third, I'm interested in promoting the Southwest as a cultural enterprise.
Romantic world.
So that's the way he cut it.
And at Texas, he ran out of steam.
Do you feel like you get any kind of direction, supervision,
from the higher administration at A&M, or do they leave you pretty much alone, or are you pretty much an independent director?
I would say that Ray Bowman does that in his year, and all the others.
I have the occasional instance where there was a time, I'm going to tell you the story, because it illustrates how

I'd like to ask you a little bit about Texas A&M University Press and its relations to other Texas presses, and particularly, I suppose, to your clients and your distributors and your associates and whoever.
Well, basically I'd say that the two major presses in Texas are UT and A&M.
UT is clearly a more important and larger press than A&M.
Frank, I think, was there longer and did a better job, had more time, of course, to do.
